<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n50082d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n50" href="#n50082d">N50 (VI.B.37)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n50all.htm#n50082d"> 82(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Ravenflok / Flok Vilgerdeson</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The ravens Hugin and Munin sat on his shoulders, and only flew away to bring him intelligence of what happened in the world. The ancient Northmen had consequently an especial confidence in the omens of Odin&apos;s bird. When the Viking <mark>Floke Vilgerdes&ouml;n</mark> set out from Norway to discover Iceland, he consecrated at a sacrifice three ravens, which he wished to take with him, to show him the way. He was therefore called <mark>Ravnefloke</mark>. <small> J.J.A. Worsaae, <a name="JJAW2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JJAW2"><cite title="source">An Account of the Danes and Norwegians in England, Scotland and Ireland</cite></a> (1852) 56f</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
